1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,667
In 1956, a Bell Labs scientist named John Kelly published a

2
00:00:04,767 --> 00:00:10,405
formula that — if applied correctly — provably maximises your long-term

3
00:00:10,505 --> 00:00:15,092
wealth growth rate faster than any other betting strategy.

4
00:00:15,183 --> 00:00:19,346
It's used by everyone from professional blackjack card counters

5
00:00:19,446 --> 00:00:22,595
to quantitative hedge funds. And it comes with a

6
00:00:22,695 --> 00:00:25,979
trap that destroys accounts if you're not careful.

7
00:00:28,566 --> 00:00:33,174
The Kelly Criterion answers one question: given a bet with known

8
00:00:33,274 --> 00:00:38,618
probabilities and payoffs, what fraction of your bankroll should you risk?

9
00:00:38,716 --> 00:00:42,192
The answer is counterintuitive — not as much as

10
00:00:42,292 --> 00:00:45,691
you think, and definitely not all of it. Today

11
00:00:45,791 --> 00:00:50,560
I'll give you the single-bet formula, the multi-asset extension,

12
00:00:50,660 --> 00:00:54,744
and the fractional Kelly approach used in real trading.

13
00:00:57,333 --> 00:01:02,489
The Kelly formula: f-star equals p minus q over b.

14
00:01:02,600 --> 00:01:08,985
p is the probability of winning. q equals one minus p — the probability

15
00:01:09,085 --> 00:01:14,740
of losing. b is the net odds: how much you win per unit risked.

16
00:01:14,833 --> 00:01:18,756
f-star is the optimal fraction of your bankroll to

17
00:01:18,856 --> 00:01:23,021
bet each time. This single formula encodes the entire

18
00:01:23,121 --> 00:01:27,045
trade-off between edge, odds, and position sizing.

19
00:01:29,633 --> 00:01:35,771
Concrete example: a fair coin where heads pays 2 to

20
00:01:35,871 --> 00:01:40,909
1. p equals 0.5, q equals 0.5, b equals 2.

21
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:45,292
Kelly says bet 25% of your bankroll each flip.

22
00:01:45,383 --> 00:01:51,676
Not 50% — that feels right but a losing streak compounds ruinously.

23
00:01:51,776 --> 00:01:57,687
Not 100% — one loss wipes you out. 25%, because the mathematics

24
00:01:57,787 --> 00:02:04,843
proves that is the exact fraction that maximises compound wealth over time.

25
00:02:07,433 --> 00:02:13,010
Kelly maximises the geometric mean — the expected value of the

26
00:02:13,110 --> 00:02:17,497
logarithm of wealth. G of f equals p times log of

27
00:02:17,597 --> 00:02:21,709
one plus f-b, plus q times log of one minus f.

28
00:02:22,800 --> 00:02:27,557
Maximise G over f. The solution is f-star at 25%.

29
00:02:27,657 --> 00:02:32,117
Notice: G rises to a peak at Kelly, then falls

30
00:02:32,217 --> 00:02:38,660
steeply. Betting more than f-star produces lower geometric growth.

31
00:02:38,750 --> 00:02:43,624
Paradoxically, overbetting makes you grow slower and eventually go

32
00:02:43,724 --> 00:02:46,789
to zero. This is the Kelly trap: a winning

33
00:02:46,889 --> 00:02:51,010
strategy played at twice Kelly will eventually ruin you.

34
00:02:54,600 --> 00:03:00,500
At 10% — well below Kelly — the bankroll grows slowly but safely.

35
00:03:00,600 --> 00:03:03,611
At full Kelly — 25% — the bankroll

36
00:03:03,711 --> 00:03:07,820
compounds at the maximum long-run growth rate.

37
00:03:07,916 --> 00:03:12,168
At 50% — twice Kelly — growth is actually slower

38
00:03:12,268 --> 00:03:16,792
than full Kelly. The extra risk is not compensated.

39
00:03:16,883 --> 00:03:23,317
At 75% — reckless overbetting — the bankroll collapses toward

40
00:03:23,417 --> 00:03:28,351
zero. A strategy with a 50% win rate, played at

41
00:03:28,451 --> 00:03:34,135
75%, will eventually ruin you. This is the Kelly trap.

42
00:03:38,033 --> 00:03:42,960
For a portfolio of N assets, the multi-asset Kelly maximises

43
00:03:43,060 --> 00:03:47,149
the expected log return over all weight vectors w.

44
00:03:47,250 --> 00:03:52,100
In the Gaussian approximation, the optimal Kelly portfolio is

45
00:03:52,200 --> 00:03:57,619
proportional to the inverse covariance matrix times expected returns

46
00:03:57,719 --> 00:04:02,326
— identical to the Markowitz tangency portfolio. Kelly and

47
00:04:02,426 --> 00:04:05,654
Markowitz converge in the Gaussian world.

48
00:04:05,750 --> 00:04:10,111
Where they diverge is in fat-tailed distributions, where

49
00:04:10,211 --> 00:04:14,572
Kelly is more conservative because log utility penalises

50
00:04:14,672 --> 00:04:19,114
extreme losses far more severely than mean-variance does.

51
00:04:21,700 --> 00:04:26,764
Full Kelly is extremely aggressive and highly sensitive to estimation

52
00:04:26,864 --> 00:04:30,132
errors in p and b. A 10% overestimate of edge

53
00:04:30,232 --> 00:04:33,576
can drive you to bet twice the optimal amount.

54
00:04:33,666 --> 00:04:38,784
In practice, traders use fractional Kelly. Half Kelly gives you

55
00:04:38,884 --> 00:04:43,008
about 75% of the long-run growth rate of full Kelly

56
00:04:43,108 --> 00:04:47,894
with dramatically lower drawdowns and variance of outcomes.

57
00:04:47,983 --> 00:04:53,584
Half-Kelly is the professional compromise between growth maximisation and

58
00:04:53,684 --> 00:04:57,099
risk control. Never use more than full Kelly.

59
00:04:59,683 --> 00:05:04,544
Applied to yield strategy selection: the Kelly fraction for

60
00:05:04,644 --> 00:05:09,927
each protocol allocation is proportional to expected yield minus

61
00:05:10,027 --> 00:05:14,216
the risk-free rate, divided by the variance of that

62
00:05:14,316 --> 00:05:20,607
yield. Higher-yielding, lower-variance protocols receive larger allocations.

63
00:05:20,700 --> 00:05:26,164
Smart contract exploit risk dramatically reduces the Kelly fraction.

64
00:05:26,264 --> 00:05:29,601
A negative 100% event has a log utility of

65
00:05:29,701 --> 00:05:34,511
negative infinity — total ruin. The Kelly fraction collapses

66
00:05:34,611 --> 00:05:39,176
to near-zero for any protocol with uncapped exploit risk.

67
00:05:39,266 --> 00:05:43,407
This is why you must explicitly price smart contract

68
00:05:43,507 --> 00:05:47,974
risk before applying Kelly to any DeFi yield allocation.

69
00:05:49,566 --> 00:05:53,766
Kelly is the long-run optimal sizing formula — but only

70
00:05:53,866 --> 00:05:59,474
when your probability estimates are accurate. Use half-Kelly in practice.

71
00:05:59,566 --> 00:06:05,954
Never use more than full Kelly — overbetting causes ruin even with positive

72
00:06:06,054 --> 00:06:11,490
edge. Always add a hard stop: Kelly is a ceiling, not a mandate.

73
00:06:11,583 --> 00:06:16,933
For DeFi: price smart contract exploit risk before applying

74
00:06:17,033 --> 00:06:21,275
Kelly. The formula is a ceiling, not a mandate.

75
00:06:21,866 --> 00:06:27,890
Next: Risk Parity — the portfolio construction method that ignores

76
00:06:27,990 --> 00:06:34,757
expected returns entirely and allocates purely based on risk contribution.

77
00:06:34,857 --> 00:06:40,510
Used by Bridgewater's All Weather fund. Subscribe. QuantiFire.

